HOUSE RESOLUTION NO. 351
BY REPRESENTATIVE BAYHAM
CONDOLENCES: Expresses the condolences of the House of Representatives on the death
of Russell M. Nelson, president of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints
1 A RESOLUTION
2 To express the condolences of the House of Representatives on the death of Russell M.
3 Nelson, president of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints.
4 WHEREAS, it is with immense sadness and profound regret that the House of
5 Representatives of the Legislature of Louisiana has learned of the passing, on September 27,
6 2025, of Russell M. Nelson, president of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints; and
7 WHEREAS, Russell Marion Nelson, Sr., was born on September 9, 1924, in Salt
8 Lake City, Utah, to Marion C. Nelson and Edna Anderson Nelson; he was the second of four
9 children, grew up in a loving home, and was baptized into the Church of Jesus Christ of
10 Latter-day Saints at the age of sixteen; and
11 WHEREAS, as a youth, President Nelson had a natural love of science, and he
12 decided as a teenager that he would study medicine in college; he attended the University
13 of Utah, where he met Dantzel White; they married on August 31, 1945, in the Salt Lake
14 Temple and had ten children; and
15 WHEREAS, because President Nelson attended college during World War II, he
16 compressed his premedical degree into three years and began medical school at the
17 University of Utah in 1944; he graduated from medical school at the top of his class; and
18 WHEREAS, President Nelson served in the United States Naval Reserve from 1945
19 to 1947; he served his residency in surgery at Massachusetts General Hospital in Boston and
20 at the University of Minnesota and received a Ph.D. in 1954; he received several honorary
21 degrees, including a doctor of science from Brigham Young University in 1970, a doctor of
